There are several ways you can achieve such a thing:

 1. `nohup java -server myApplication.jar &gt; /log.txt` - this is pretty straight forward. It will just put the application in the background. This will work but it&#39;s just not a very good way to do so.
 2. Use a shell wrapper and the above OR [daemon](http://www.libslack.org/daemon/) app. This approach is used by many open source projects and it&#39;s quite good for most of the scenarios. Additionally it can be included in `init.d` and required run level with regular start, stop and status commands. I can provide an example if needed.
 3. Build your own daemon server using either [Java Service Wrapper](http://wrapper.tanukisoftware.com/) or [Apache Jakarta Commons Daemon](http://commons.apache.org/daemon/). Again - both are extremely popular, well tested and reliable. And available for both Linux and Windows! The one from Apache Commons is used by Tomcat server! Additionally there is [Akuma](http://akuma.kohsuke.org/).

Personally I would go with solution 2 or 3 if you need to use this server in the future and/or distribute it to clients, end users, etc. `nohup` is good if you need to run something and have no time to develop more complex solution for the problem.

