# An enum is a limited set of named objects of the same type

You misunderstand the purpose of an enum in Java. As stated in the [*Java Language Specification*][1], an enum “defines a small set of named class instances”. So all the objects named in the enum must be of the same type. That type is the `Enum` subclass on which they are declared.

For example: 

 - `enum Rgb { RED , GREEN , BLUE }`
 - `enum CountryInUk { ENGLAND , NORTHERN_IRELAND , SCOTLAND , WALES }`
 - `enum Flavor { VANILLA , CHOCOLATE , STRAWBERRY }`

Each named object in an `Enum` subclass is of the same type. So any member property you add will be present in each and every named object. 

In this next example we add the member property `hex` of type `String` to each of the `Rgb` enum objects seen above. 

    enum Rgb { 
        RED( &quot;FF0000&quot; ) , GREEN( &quot;00FF00&quot; ) , BLUE( &quot;0000FF&quot; ) ;
        private String hex ; // Hexadecimal representation. 
        private Rgb( String hex ) { this.hex = hex ; } ;
        public String getHex() { return this.hex ; }
    }

# Ways to associate objects

If you want to associate various objects together by name, use the other features of Java.

You could define a `Map` to track a collection of key-value pairs. See [tutorial][2] by Oracle.

    Map&lt; String, LocalDate &gt; contracts = new HashMap&lt;&gt;() ;
    contracts.put( someContractorName , someHireDate ) ;
    contracts.put( otherContractorName , otherHireDate ) ;

Or define a class to hold the parts together. If the main purpose of the class is to carry data transparently and immutably, define your class as a [record][3].

    record Contract ( String contractorName , LocalDate whenHired ) {}
    Contract pavement = new Contract ( &quot;Acme Pavement Company&quot; , LocalDate.of( 2023, Month.JANUARY , 23 ) ) ;


  [1]: https://docs.oracle.com/javase/specs/jls/se17/html/jls-8.html#jls-8.9
  [2]: https://docs.oracle.com/javase/tutorial/collections/interfaces/map.html
  [3]: https://openjdk.java.net/jeps/395

